// INITIAL PROJECT SETUP AND OSM MODEL
Before any spatial indexing or rendering work started, I set up the initial project structure — Maven build, .gitignore, and the main entry point. I then created all the core OSM domain model classes: Coordinate as an immutable lat/lon record, Element as the abstract base for all OSM elements with tag management, and Node, Way, and Relation extending it. Member was added as a record pairing an element with an optional role string, used inside relations. I also introduced the first version of the MBR (Minimum Bounding Rectangle) class as a record holding minLat, minLon, maxLat, and maxLon, and refactored Element so that all subclasses could compute and store their bounding box in a consistent place. The calcMBR helper that derived a bounding box from a list of nodes was eventually moved into Element as a shared static method so that Way and Relation could both call it without duplicating logic.

// SPATIAL GEOMETRY AND DATA MODEL
Early in the project I introduced the BoundingBox class as a proper spatial record to replace the scattered double-arrays that were previously used to represent minimum bounding rectangles. I refactored the MBR logic across the Node, Way, and Relation classes so that each element computed its own bounds correctly — Ways used the shoelace formula to get a proper polygon area, and Relations aggregated bounds from their members recursively. I also introduced a SpatialElement interface and an OsmElement abstract class to give the model a cleaner hierarchy, and later added lazy MBR computation so bounds were only finalised once an element was fully constructed.

// R-TREE DESIGN AND IMPLEMENTATION
My main responsibility for the data layer was designing and implementing the R-tree spatial index. I started with a skeleton and a detailed plan of the insert, search, and split operations, then worked through a first implementation with separate internal and leaf node subclasses. That approach got complicated quickly, so I scrapped it and rewrote the tree from scratch using a sealed entry hierarchy — LeafEntry and NodeEntry records — which made the split and adjustment logic much cleaner. The final implementation had all the core R-tree algorithms: chooseLeaf for guided insertion, adjustTree to propagate MBR changes up the tree after inserts, and a quadratic splitNode with pickSeeds and pickNext for node overflow. I also moved the whole package from the prototype namespace into models.RTree as part of a broader reorganisation.

// INTEGRATION WITH PARSER AND RENDERING
Once the tree was working in isolation I wired it into the parsing and rendering pipeline. The parser populates the tree during a single pass over the OSM data, and the application then queries the tree at draw time using a viewport bounding box. I added getViewportBox to derive the query box from the current canvas transform, and refactored the renderer lists to be updated from Tree.search results on every redraw. I also introduced SearchResults as a typed container so the tree could return nodes, ways, and relations separately, and added sorting by area descending inside SearchResults so larger polygons always rendered below smaller ones. I later added zoom-level LOD pruning directly into the tree search: each internal node tracks the minimum zoom level of its subtree, so branches containing only fine-detail elements are skipped entirely at lower zoom levels without visiting their leaves.

// NEAREST NEIGHBOR SEARCH
I implemented the nearest-node search that the pathfinding UI relies on to snap click positions to real graph nodes. The approach uses an expanding bounding box — starting at a small radius around the cursor and doubling it until at least one node is found. I extended this to collect nodes not just from direct leaf entries but also from the node lists inside Ways and Relations, which was necessary to get good coverage across the full graph.

// APPLICATION ARCHITECTURE REFACTORING
I did several rounds of architectural refactoring to keep the growing codebase manageable. Early on I extracted relation parsing into its own method in the parser and switched to a switch statement for the XML element dispatch. Later I introduced AppData as a shared state holder, split the monolithic App class into AppController, EventHandler, and UserInterface, and promoted both parsers to extend a common AbstractParser base. I also introduced AppSettings as a singleton for rendering flags so that things like height-curve visibility could be queried from anywhere without threading state through constructor arguments.

// PATHFINDING
I built out the pathfinding integration on the application side. I created PathfindingObject as a singleton holding the start and end node as reactive ObjectProperty fields, wrote the UI interaction logic for clicking to set locations, and connected the selection state to the label display. I also added keyboard shortcuts for switching between select and explore modes. On the algorithm side I replaced the early Dijkstra prototype with a new Pathfinder class that supports both Dijkstra and A* through a single boolean flag, using haversine distance for geo-accurate edge weights and heuristics. The OsmParser was extended to build the road graph during parsing, respecting one-way tags. After getting A* running I spent time debugging the algorithm and fixing an edge case in the priority ordering, and added a GraphicsRenderer to draw the computed route on the map.

// PERFORMANCE OPTIMIZATION AND BENCHMARKING
Towards the end of the project I focused on identifying and fixing performance bottlenecks. I added area caching to BoundingBox to avoid recalculating the same value repeatedly during search and sort, and switched SearchResults.sort to Arrays.parallelSort which gave roughly a 2.7x speedup on large result sets. I also set up a JMH benchmarking framework from scratch — adding the Maven JMH plugin, writing TreeBuildBenchmark and TreeSearchBenchmark, and creating a BenchmarkUtils class to share setup code. I expanded this into several benchmark categories covering viewport scaling, nearest-neighbor performance, and a direct tree versus linear scan comparison. I benchmarked the AdaptivePath pixel_step parameter across five configurations to find a good performance-quality tradeoff. One concrete result from all this was identifying 8192 as the optimal threshold for switching SearchResults from sequential to parallel sorting — below that the overhead of parallelism is not worth it, above it the speedup is consistent and meaningful. I also fixed a bug in TreeData.size() that was returning the wrong element count, which had been causing the renderer to undercount how many elements it needed to process.
